The paper deals with mechanism design problems, which are typically studied in the field of computational game theory (cs.GT). The techniques used in the paper involve analyzing the approximation ratios of truthful mechanisms, which is a topic of interest in algorithmic mechanism design (cs.DS). The paper also discusses Bayesian mechanisms, which are studied in the field of information theory (cs.IT). The use of randomized mechanisms and the analysis of fairness notions suggest a connection to the field of machine learning (cs.LG). Finally, the paper deals with network routing problems, which are studied in the field of network economics (cs.NE).
